                                <condition>
                                    <p>
                                        The cave is full of hill of natural fissures and copious graffiti, with sufficient weathering of the inscription. This condition of the stone does not rule out the possibility that letters have been lost from the beginning and end of this inscription (Forsyth 1996, 94-96).
                                    </p>
                                </condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>
                                    <p>
                                       The inscription is carved on the left-hand wall of the cave, about <height unit="m">2</height> above the present floor. It is about <dim type="depth" unit="m">9</dim> from the entrance gate with a panel of snake-like, loose spirla interlace graffiti in the same area (Forsyth 1996, 94-95). 
                                    </p>
                                </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>
                                <rs type="execution" key="carved" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/168.html">Carved</rs>
                                <p>
                                   The stem line runs vertically between two patches of wear, the lower <height unit="cm">26</height>, the upper <height unit="cm">8.4</height>.
Immediately afier the end of the upper patch there is a clear cross-stroke where the stem appears to end. There is a potential similar stroke below the lower patch, but not absolutely clear. These two end-strokes are about <dim type="length" unit="m">0.500</dim> apart. Nothing is visible in the upper patch of 
wear, in the lower there may be traces of occasional strokes, but these are very faint (Forsyth 1996, 94).    
                                </p>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
